predictions.rationale: The student correctly explains major plate-boundary processes (convergence, subduction, transform) and links subduction to the Ring of Fire, but shows uncertainty and gives somewhat vague/incomplete explanations at times.

The student shows a mostly correct core model (right heart to lungs, left to body) and corrects the artery/oxygen misconception by the end, but has shaky terminology and needs prompting to resolve confusion.

The student can apply the Pythagorean theorem and correct a key mistake (taking the square root) and verify a 5-12-13 triple, but still shows confusion about setting up the equation when the hypotenuse is given.

Shows partial understanding of Newton’s laws and friction but has repeated misconceptions (e.g., multiplying numbers by default, unequal action–reaction forces) and relies on uncertainty rather than consistent reasoning.
Der Schüler zeigt überwiegend korrektes Verständnis zu Ordnungszahl/Massenzahl, Gruppen/Perioden und Ionen (mit etwas Unsicherheit und Verwechslungen, die er aber teils selbst klärt).
The student can compute slope from two points and correctly find the intercept by substitution, showing some uncertainty but also self-correction and verification.
The student gives accurate, well-explained answers with strong causal reasoning, applies ideas to new analogies (Luddites vs. AI), and shows curiosity and nuanced source evaluation.
Shows some basic ideas (current as flow, series vs parallel intuition) but has major misconceptions about voltage being “used up/lost” and inconsistent reasoning that needs frequent correction.
The student gives accurate, detailed explanations of key French Revolution concepts and events with clear causal reasoning and confident connections, with only minor oversimplifications.
Shows some basic acid/base associations and guesses about neutralization and OH−, but has major confusion about ions/charges and dissociation with frequent misconceptions and low confidence.

The student uses precise writing/analysis vocabulary (thesis, counter-argument, PEEL, method/effect), gives strong examples, self-corrects toward analysis over summary, and asks a clarifying follow-up question.

Shows partial understanding of factoring/zero-product and can compute a vertex when guided, but is unsure of core ideas and cannot independently use key methods like the quadratic formula or completing the square.

The student uses precise literary terminology correctly (theme, motif, symbolism, unreliable narration), offers diagnostic criteria and alternative hypotheses, and demonstrates transfer and metacognitive engagement by pushing toward deeper socio-economic implications.

The student uses precise domain vocabulary correctly, gives well-supported interpretations with metacognitive nuance, and transfers concepts across authors/works while posing deeper analytical questions.

Uses precise molecular biology terminology correctly (initiation factors, Kozak/leaky scanning, NMD, IRES controls), reasons through edge cases, and self-initiates deeper questions with strong transfer to new scenarios.

Shows strong, mostly correct chemistry reasoning with transfer to limiting reagents, gas laws, equilibrium, and defect chemistry, plus metacognitive checking of inconsistent data, though a few answers are context-fragile/possibly incorrect (e.g., CaCO3 mass from gas moles) and some responses rely on assumptions.

Der Schüler nutzt präzise Thermodynamik-Begriffe und -Gleichungen korrekt, reflektiert Vorzeichenkonventionen, erklärt Irreversibilität/Entropie mikroskopisch und transferiert selbstständig zu Maxwell-Relationen und Joule-Thomson mit weiterführenden Fragen.

Student uses precise wave/interference vocabulary, applies formulas correctly (including unequal intensities and polarization), explains reasoning, and self-initiates deeper extensions and assumptions.

The student uses precise historical vocabulary accurately, offers nuanced causal reasoning with historiographical framing, and proactively transfers knowledge by posing deeper, well-targeted follow-up questions.

The student correctly computes basic probabilities and uses the independence test (P(A∩B)=P(A)P(B)) with some initial confusion and a minor intersection mistake that they self-correct through reasoning.
Shows basic familiarity with DNA/chromosomes/alleles and recessive vs dominant ideas but has major misconceptions about mutations/protein coding and relies on vague guesses without solid reasoning.

The student correctly defines wavelength/frequency and uses v=fλ to reason about changes and do calculations, but shows confusion about what affects wave speed on a rope and about particle speed vs wave speed.

The student gives generally correct definitions and examples (theme, unreliable narrator, symbolism) and can refine phrasing, but explanations stay somewhat vague and lack concrete textual evidence or deeper generalization.

Zeigt solides Grundverständnis der Romantik (Motive, Epochenabgrenzung, Hoffmann/Sandmann) und kann Beispiele erklären, hat aber Unsicherheiten bei Fachbegriffen/Einordnung (z.B. Universalpoesie, Periodisierung) und einzelne ungenaue Zuordnungen.

Shows some intuitive ideas (compression warms gas, water bath keeps temperature) but repeatedly confuses core concepts like heat vs internal energy and sign conventions, relying on guesses and admitting fragile understanding.
